# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andreas-von-bülow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Various conspiracy theories attribute the preparation and execution of the September 11 attacks against the United States to parties other than, or in addition to, al-Qaeda.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] These include the theory that high-level government officials had advance knowledge of the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Government investigations and independent reviews have rejected these theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Proponents of these theories assert that there are inconsistencies in the commonly accepted version, or that there is evidence that was ignored, concealed, or overlooked.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Most of these theories either lack evidence or have been debunked by experts.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The most prominent conspiracy theory is that the collapse of the Twin Towers and 7 World Trade Center were the result of controlled demolitions rather than structural failure due to impact and fire.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Another prominent belief is that the Pentagon was hit by a missile launched by elements from inside the U.S. government, or that hijacked planes were remotely controlled, or that commercial airliners were allowed to hit the targets via an effective stand-down of the U.S. military.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Other conspiracy theories revolve around authorities having advance knowledge of the attacks and deliberately ignoring or assisting the attackers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and the technology magazine *Popular Mechanics* investigated and rejected these theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Since the attacks, various conspiracy theories have been advanced in websites, books and films.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Many groups and individuals advocating 9/11 conspiracy theories identify as part of the 9/11 Truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Within six hours of the attack, a suggestion appeared in an online chatroom suggesting that the towers' collapse looked like a controlled demolition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One false allegation that circulated widely online is that no Jews were killed in the attack and that therefore the attacks must have been the work of the Mossad, not Islamist terrorists.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The first elaborated theories appeared in Europe.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One week after the attacks, the "inside job" theory was the subject of a thesis by a researcher from the French National Centre for Scientific Research published in the newspaper *Le Monde*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Other theories sprang from around the world within weeks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Six months after the attacks, Thierry Meyssan's piece on 9/11, *L'Effroyable Imposture* (*The Terrible Deceit*), topped the French bestseller list.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Its publication in English (as *9/11: The Big Lie*) received little attention, but it remains one of the principal sources for "trutherism".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] 2003 saw the publication of former German state minister Andreas von Bülow's *The CIA and September 11* and German journalist Gerhard Wisnewski's *Operation 9/11*; both were published by Mathias Bröckers, at the time an editor at the German newspaper *Die Tageszeitung*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] While these theories were popular in Europe, the U.S. media treated them with either bafflement or amusement, and the U.S. government dismissed them as the product of anti-Americanism.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In an address to the United Nations on November 10, 2001, President George W.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Bush denounced the "outrageous conspiracy theories [...] that attempt to shift the blame away from the terrorists, themselves, away from the guilty".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The 9/11 conspiracy theories started out mostly on the political left but broadened into what *New York* magazine described in 2011 as "terra incognita where left and right meet, fusing sixties countercultural distrust with the don't-tread-on-me variety".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] By 2004, conspiracy theories about the attacks began to gain ground in the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One explanation is that the rise in popularity stemmed more from growing criticism of the Iraq War and the newly reelected President Bush than from any discovery of new or more compelling evidence or improvement in the technical quality of the presentation of the theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Knight Ridder news theorized that revelations that weapons of mass destruction did not exist in Iraq, the belated release of the President's Daily Brief of August 6, 2001, and reports that NORAD had lied to the 9/11 Commission might have fueled the theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Between 2004 and the fifth anniversary of the attacks in 2006, mainstream coverage of the conspiracy theories increased.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The U.S. government issued a formal analysis by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) of the collapse of the World Trade Center.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] To address the growing publicity of the theories, the State Department revised a webpage in 2006 to debunk them.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A 2006 national security strategy paper said that terrorism springs from "subcultures of conspiracy and misinformation" and that "terrorists recruit more effectively from populations whose information about the world is contaminated by falsehoods and corrupted by conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some of the conspiracy theories about the attacks do not involve representational strategies typical of many conspiracy theories that establish a clear dichotomy between good and evil, or guilty and innocent; instead, they call up gradations of negligence and complicity.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Bröckers, an early proponent of such theories, dismisses the commonly accepted account of the attacks as itself a conspiracy theory that seeks "to reduce complexity, disentangle what is confusing" and "explain the inexplicable".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Just before the fifth anniversary of the attacks, mainstream news outlets released a flurry of articles on the growth of 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] *Time* wrote: "This is not a fringe phenomenon.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] It is a mainstream political reality." Several surveys have included questions about beliefs related to the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In 2008, 9/11 conspiracy theories topped a "greatest conspiracy theory" list compiled by *The Daily Telegraph*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The list was ranked by following and traction.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In 2010, the "International Center for 9/11 Studies", a private organization said to be sympathetic to conspiracy theories, sued for the release of videos collected by NIST of the attacks and aftermath.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to the German daily *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung*, the videos that were published shortly before the ninth anniversary of the attacks provided "new food for conspiracy theorists".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Many of the videos show images of 7 World Trade Center, a skyscraper in the vicinity of the Twin Towers that also collapsed on September 11, 2001.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones and Mike Berger have said that the death of Osama bin Laden did not change their questions about the attacks or provide closure.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to writer Jeremy Stahl, since Bush left office, the number of believers in 9/11 conspiracy theories has decreased, but the number of people who believe in the most "radical" theories has held fairly steady.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Conspiracy theorists claim that action or inaction by U.S. officials with foreknowledge was intended to ensure that the attacks took place successfully.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] For example, Michael Meacher, former British environment minister and member of Tony Blair's government, said that the United States knowingly failed to prevent the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some conspiracy theorists maintain that just before 9/11, an "extraordinary" amount of put options were placed on United Airlines and American Airlines stocks and speculate that insiders may have known in advance of the coming events of 9/11 and placed their bets accordingly.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In the days leading up to 9/11, analysis shows a rise in the put to call ratio for United Airlines and American Airlines, the two airlines from which planes were hijacked on 9/11.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Between September 6 and 7, the Chicago Board Options Exchange recorded purchases of 4,744 "put" option contracts in UAL and 396 call options.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] On September 10, more trading in Chicago saw the purchase of 4,516 put options in American Airlines, the other airline involved in the hijackings, with a mere 748 call options in American purchased that day.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] No other airline companies had an unusual put to call ratio in the days leading up to the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The 9/11 Commission concluded that all these abnormal patterns in trading were coincidental.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Insurance companies saw anomalous trading activities as well.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Citigroup Inc., which estimated that its Travelers Insurance unit could pay $500 million in claims from the World Trade Center attack, had about 45 times the normal volume during three trading days before the attack for options that profit, if the stock falls below $40.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Citigroup shares fell $1.25 in late trading to $38.09.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Morgan Stanley, which occupied 22 floors at the World Trade Center, experienced bigger-than-normal pre-attack trading of options that profited when stock prices fell.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Other companies directly affected by the tragedy had similar jumps.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The initial options were bought through at least two brokerage firms, including NFS, a subsidiary of Fidelity Investments, and TD Waterhouse.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] It was estimated that the trader or traders would have realized a five million dollar profit.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The Securities and Exchange Commission launched an insider trading investigation in which Osama bin Laden was a suspect after receiving information from at least one Wall Street Firm.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A common claim among conspiracy theorists is that the North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD) issued a stand down order or deliberately scrambled fighters late to allow the hijacked airplanes to reach their targets without interference.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to this theory, NORAD had the capability of locating and intercepting planes on 9/11, and its failure to do so indicates a government conspiracy to allow the attacks to occur.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Elsis said: "There is only one explanation for this ...
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One of the first actions taken by the hijackers on 9/11 was to turn off or disable each of the four aircraft's on board transponders.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Without these transponder signals to identify the airplane's tail number, altitude, and speed, the hijacked airplanes would have been only blips among 4,500 other blips on NORAD's radar screens, making them very difficult to track.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] On 9/11, only 14 fighter jets were on alert in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] There was no automated method for the civilian air traffic controllers to alert NORAD.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A passenger aircraft had not been hijacked in the U.S. since 1979.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Douglas Martin, public affairs officer for NORAD, stated that "They had to pick up the phone and literally dial us".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Only one civilian plane—a chartered Learjet 35 with golfer Payne Stewart and five others on board—was intercepted by NORAD over North America in the decade prior to 9/11, which took one hour and 19 minutes.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Rules in effect at that time, and on 9/11, barred supersonic flight on intercepts.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Before 9/11, all other NORAD interceptions were limited to offshore Air Defense Identification Zones (ADIZ).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] FAA spokesman Bill Schumann said that "Until 9/11 there was no domestic ADIZ".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] After 9/11, the FAA and NORAD increased cooperation.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] They set up hotlines between command centers while NORAD increased its fighter coverage and installed radar to watch airspace over the continent.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The longest warning NORAD received of the hijackings was some eight minutes for American Airlines Flight 11, the first flight hijacked.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The FAA alerted NORAD to the hijacked Flight 175 at just about the same time it was crashing into the World Trade Center's South Tower.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The FAA notified NORAD of the missing – not hijacked – Flight 77 three minutes before it struck the Pentagon.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Regarding United Airlines Flight 93, Major General Larry Arnold indicated that there had been time to intercept the plane.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] However, NORAD was awaiting authorization to shoot it down, a decision that was ultimately made unnecessary by the actions of the passengers who stormed the cockpit, leading to the plane's crash in a field near Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] It has been claimed that Israeli agents may have had foreknowledge of the attacks, and a persistent theory claimed Israeli and/or Jewish involvement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Four hours after the attack, the FBI arrested five Israelis who had been filming the smoking skyline from the roof of a white van in the parking lot of an apartment building.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The Israelis were videotaping the events, and one bystander said they acted in a suspicious manner: "They were like happy, you know ...
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The case was then moved to the FBI's Foreign Counterintelligence Section.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The collapse of the World Trade Center's North and South Towers was attributed by official investigations, including those conducted by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), to structural damage caused by the plane impacts and subsequent fires.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] 7 World Trade Center, which was not hit by a plane, collapsed later in the day due to fires ignited by debris from the North Tower.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Controlled demolition conspiracy theories claim that all three buildings were brought down by pre-installed explosives, but these ideas have been widely dismissed by experts due to a lack of evidence.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Demolition theory proponents, such as physicist Steven E.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones, architect Richard Gage, software engineer Jim Hoffman, and theologian David Ray Griffin, argue that the aircraft impacts and subsequent fires were insufficient to explain the catastrophic collapses of the Twin Towers and World Trade Center 7.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones, in his paper, posits that evidence of thermite reactions points to controlled demolition as the cause.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Gage presents architectural and engineering analyses arguing that fire alone could not have caused the observed structural failures.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Hoffman disputes the official explanations, highlighting inconsistencies in the collapse dynamics.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Griffin challenges mainstream attempts to refute these theories, contending that alternative explanations better account for the evidence.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones, and others claim to have identified thermite and nano-thermite composites in the dust and debris following the collapse of the three World Trade Center buildings.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] However, this claim has been challenged by materials scientist Dr.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Millette, whose independent analysis, detailed in a technical report released in 2012, concluded that the red/gray chips examined were consistent with common construction materials, specifically a carbon steel coated with epoxy resin containing iron oxide and kaolin, used in building paint.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Unlike Harrit et al.’s article, which was published in a peer-reviewed journal, Millette’s report was not peer-reviewed but has been widely cited in discussions on the topic.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Millette’s findings cast doubt on the thermite hypothesis, suggesting the chips were not evidence of an explosive material.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The article by Harrit et al. contained no formal scientific rebuttal at the time of publication, but the editor-in-chief of the *Open Chemical Physics Journal* later resigned, adding to the controversy surrounding the study.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones has not explained how the amount of explosive needed to bring down the buildings could have been positioned in the two buildings without drawing attention, but mentioned efforts to research the buildings' maintenance activity in the weeks prior to the event.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Federal investigators at the National Institute of Standards and Technology state that enormous quantities of thermite would have to be applied to the structural columns to damage them, but Jones disputed this, saying that he and others were investigating "superthermite".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Other sampling of the pulverized dust by United States Geological Survey and RJ Lee did not report any evidence of thermite or explosives.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] It has been theorized the "thermite material" found was primer paint.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Dave Thomas of *Skeptical Inquirer* magazine, noting that the residue in question was claimed to be thermotic because of its iron oxide and aluminum composition, pointed out that these substances are found in many items common to the towers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Thomas said that in order to cut through a vertical steel beam, special high-temperature containment must be added to prevent the molten iron from dropping down, and that the thermite reaction is too slow for it to be practically used in building demolition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Thomas pointed out that when Jesse Ventura hired New Mexico Tech to conduct a demonstration showing nanothermite slicing through a large steel beam, the nanothermite produced copious flame and smoke but no damage to the beam, even though it was in a horizontal, and therefore optimal, position.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) concluded the accepted version was more than sufficient to explain the collapse of the buildings.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] NIST and many scientists have refused to debate conspiracy theorists because they feel it would give those theories unwarranted credibility.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Specialists in structural mechanics and structural engineering accept the model of a fire-induced, gravity-driven collapse of the World Trade Center buildings without the use of explosives.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] As a result, NIST said that it did not perform any test for the residue of explosive compounds of any kind in the debris.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Soon after the day of the attacks, major media sources published that the towers had collapsed due to heat melting the steel.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] While the theoretical adiabatic flame temperature of kerosene is 2,093°C, this assumes perfect conditions, such as no heat loss and complete combustion in a stoichiometric mix of pure oxygen.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In real-world conditions, such as burning kerosene in normal air, flame temperatures typically range from 260°C to 315°C.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] These temperatures are far below the melting point of structural steel (1,539°C).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] However, steel loses approximately 50% of its strength at 600°C and around 90% at 980°C.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] This weakening, combined with the removal of fireproofing by the initial impact and prolonged exposure to fire, may have contributed to the structural failures observed during the collapse of the World Trade Center towers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Further, NIST did not claim that the steel melted, but rather that heat softened and weakened the steel, and that weakening, together with the damage caused by the planes' impacts, caused structural collapse.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] NIST reported that a simulation model based on the simple assumption that combustible vapors burned immediately upon mixing with the incoming air showed that "at any given location, the duration of gas temperatures near 1,000 °C was about 15 to 20 minutes.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Political activist Thierry Meyssan and filmmaker Dylan Avery claim that American Airlines Flight 77 did not crash into the Pentagon.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Instead, they argue that the Pentagon was hit by a missile launched by elements from inside the U.S. government.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] When released, the book was heavily criticized by both the mainstream French and American press, and later, from within the 9/11 Truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In response to the conspiracy theorists' claim of a missile hitting the Pentagon, Mete Sozen, a professor of civil engineering at Purdue University argues that: "A crashing jet doesn't punch a cartoon-like outline of itself into a reinforced concrete building.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] When Flight 77 hit the Pentagon, one wing hit the ground and the other was sheared off by the Pentagon's load-bearing columns." According to *ArchitectureWeek*, the reason the Pentagon took relatively little damage from the impact was because Wedge One had recently been renovated.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The evidence refuting missile claims includes airplane debris including Flight 77's black boxes, the nose cone, landing gear, an airplane tire, and an intact cockpit seat were observed at the crash site.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The remains of passengers from Flight 77 were indeed found at the Pentagon crash site and their identities confirmed by DNA analysis.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Foreign governments, such as the Chinese Foreign Ministry (FMPRC), also confirms the death of their citizens onboard Flight 77.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Many eyewitnesses saw the plane strike the Pentagon, and multiple survivors of the impact zone of the Pentagon have described the smell of jet fuel from the crashed Flight 77 in their recollections of the attack.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Further, Flight 77 passengers made phone calls reporting that their airplane had been hijacked.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] For example, passenger Renee May called her mother to tell her that the plane had been hijacked and that the passengers had been herded to the back of the plane.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Another passenger named Barbara Olson called her husband (U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Solicitor General Theodore Olson) and said that the flight had been hijacked, and that the hijackers had knives and box cutters.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some conspiracy theories say the phone calls the passengers made were fabricated by voice morphing, the passengers' bodies disposed of, and a missile fired at the Pentagon.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The pressure group Judicial Watch filed a Freedom of Information Act request on December 15, 2004, to force the government to release video recordings from the Sheraton National Hotel, the Nexcomm/Citgo gas station, Pentagon security cameras and the Virginia Department of Transportation.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] On May 16, 2006, the government released the Pentagon security camera videos to Judicial Watch.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The image of American Airlines Flight 77 which appears in the videos has been described as "[a] white blob" and "a white streak" (by the BBC), "a thin white blur" (by the Associated Press), and "a silver speck low to the ground" (in *The Washington Post*).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A sequence of five frames from one of the videos already appeared in the media in 2002.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some conspiracy theorists believe the new video does not answer their questions.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The fourth plane hijacked on 9/11, United Airlines Flight 93, crashed in an open field near Shanksville, Pennsylvania, after the passengers revolted.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Out of the four planes hijacked on that day, Flight 93 was the only one not to reach its target.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One conspiracy theory surrounding this event is the claim that Flight 93 was shot down by a U.S. fighter jet.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] David Ray Griffin and Alex Jones have asserted that large parts of the plane, including the main body of the engine, landed miles away from the main wreckage site, too far away for an ordinary plane crash.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Jones says that planes usually leave a small debris field when they crash, and that this is not compatible with reports of wreckage found farther away from the main crash site.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] One person claimed that the main body of the engine was found miles away from the main wreckage site with damage comparable to that which a heat-seeking missile would do to an airliner.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to some theories, the plane had to be shot down by the government because passengers had found out about the alleged plot.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to Phil Molé of *Skeptic* magazine, "[this] claim rests largely on unsupported assertions that the main body of the engine and other large parts of the plane turned up miles from the main wreckage site, too far away to have resulted from an ordinary crash.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] This claim is incorrect, because the engine was found only 300 yards from the main crash site, and its location was consistent with the direction in which the plane had been traveling." Michael K.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Hynes, an airline accident expert who investigated the crash of TWA Flight 800 in 1996, says that, at very high velocities of 500 mph or more, it would only take a few seconds to move or tumble across the ground for 300 yards.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Reports of wreckage discovered at Indian Lake by local residents are accurate.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] CNN reported that investigators found debris from the crash at least eight miles away from the crash site, including in New Baltimore.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to CNN, this debris was all very light material that the wind would have easily blown away, and a *Pittsburgh Post-Gazette* article from September 14, 2001, describes the material as "mostly papers", "strands of charred insulation", and an "endorsed paycheck".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The same article quotes FBI agent Bill Crowley that, "Lighter, smaller debris probably shot into the air on the heat of a fireball that witnesses said shot several hundred feet into the air after the jetliner crashed.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Then, it probably rode a wind that was blowing southeast at about 9 m.p.h." Also, the distance between the crash site and Indian Lake was misreported in some accounts.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to the BBC, "In a straight line, Indian Lake is just over a mile from the crash site.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some conspiracy theorists believe a small white jet seen flying over the crash area may have fired a missile to shoot down Flight 93.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Government agencies such as the FBI assert this small plane was a Dassault Falcon business jet asked to descend to an altitude of around 1,500 ft to survey the impact.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Ben Sliney, who was the FAA operation manager on September 11, 2001, says no military aircraft were near Flight 93.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some internet videos, such as *Loose Change*, speculate that Flight 93 safely landed in Ohio, and a substituted plane was involved in the crash in Pennsylvania.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Often cited is a preliminary news report that Flight 93 landed at a Cleveland airport; it was later learned that Delta Flight 1989 was the plane confused with Flight 93, and the report was retracted as inaccurate.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The editor of the article has since written a rebuttal to the claims.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Valencia McClatchey, a local woman who took the only photograph of the mushroom cloud from the impact of Flight 93 seconds after it hit the ground, says she has been harassed over the telephone and in person by conspiracy theorists, who claim she faked the photo.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The FBI, the Somerset County authorities, the Smithsonian, and the National Park Service's Flight 93 National Memorial staff have all individually examined the photograph as well as the film negatives and all four agencies consider the photo to be authentic.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] While some conspiracy theorists have claimed that passengers of Flight 93 and/or Flight 77 were murdered or that they were relocated, with the intent that they never be found, others within the 9/11 Truth Movement, such as Jim Hoffman and Scholars for 9/11 Truth & Justice, repudiate such claims.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] During the initial confusion surrounding the immediate aftermath of the September 11 attacks, the BBC published the names and identities of what they believed to be some of the hijackers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some of the people named were later discovered to be alive, a fact that was seized upon by 9/11 conspiracy theorists as proof that the hijackings were faked.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The BBC explained that the initial confusion may have arisen because the names they reported back in 2001 were common Arabic and Islamic names.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In response to a request from the BBC, the FBI said that it was confident to have identified all nineteen hijackers, and that none of the other inquiries had raised the issue of doubt about their identities.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] *The New York Times* also acknowledged these as cases of mistaken identity.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to John Bradley, the former managing editor of *Arab News* in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, the only public information about the hijackers was a list of names issued by the FBI on September 14, 2001.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] When the FBI released photographs four days after the cited reports on September 27, the mistaken identities were quickly resolved.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to Bradley, "all of this is attributable to the chaos that prevailed during the first few days following the attack.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to Thomas Kean, chair of the 9/11 Commission, "Sixteen of the nineteen shouldn't have gotten into the United States in any way at all because there was something wrong with their visas, something wrong with their passports.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] They should simply have been stopped at the border.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Khalid al-Mihdhar and Nawaf al-Hazmi had both been identified as al-Qaeda agents by the CIA, but that information was not shared with the FBI or U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Immigration, so both men were able to legally enter the U.S. to prepare for the 9/11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] There are allegations that individuals within the Pakistani Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI) may have played an important role in financing the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] There are also claims that other foreign intelligence agencies, such as the Israeli Mossad, had foreknowledge of the attacks, and that some Saudi officials may have played a role in financing the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] General Hamid Gul, a former head of ISI, believes the attacks were an "inside job" originating in the United States, perpetrated by Israel or neo-conservatives.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Francesco Cossiga, former President of Italy from 1985 until his 1992 resignation over Operation Gladio, said that it is common knowledge among the Italian center-left that the 9/11 attacks were a joint operation of the CIA and the Mossad.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Subsequent reports indicated that he did not actually believe this.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A conspiracy theory documented by the Anti-Defamation League, Thom Burnett and others is that the state of Israel was involved in the attacks, and may have planned them.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A variety of motives are suggested, including: to cause the United States to attack enemies of Israel; to divert public attention away from Israel's treatment of the Palestinians; to help Zionists take control of world affairs; and to persuade Americans to support Israel.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Variants of the theory contend that the attack was organized by then-Israeli prime minister Ariel Sharon, the intelligence agency Mossad, or other actors from the Israeli government.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some proponents of this theory believe that Jewish employees were forewarned by Israeli intelligence to skip work on September 11, resulting in no Jewish deaths at the World Trade Center.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to Cinnamon Stillwell, some 9/11 conspiracy theorists put this number as high as 4,000 Jewish people skipping work.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The number of Jews who died in the attacks is variously estimated at between 270 and 400.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The lower figure tracks closely with the percentage of Jews living in the New York area and partial surveys of the victims' listed religion.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] State Department has published a partial list of 76, in response to claims that fewer Jews or Israelis died in the WTC attacks than should have been present at the time.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Five Israeli citizens died in the attack.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The ADL's report found that "The Big Lie has united American far-right extremists and white supremacists and elements within the Arab and Muslim world".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] It asserted that many of the theories were modern manifestation of the 19th-century *Protocols of the Elders of Zion*, which purported to map out a Jewish conspiracy for world domination.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Sanjuan, a former United Nations diplomat, alleged that antisemitic 9/11 conspiracy theories were quite common at high levels of the organization following the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] British investigative journalists Anthony Summers and Robbyn Swan claimed in their 2011 book *The Eleventh Day* that the Saudi Royal Family provided material and financial support to the hijackers and that the Bush Administration covered this up as well as their own alleged incompetence.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] The authors claim the 9/11 Truth movement helped this coverup by deflecting attention away from these actions.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In September 2011 a "Lloyd's insurance syndicate" began legal action against Saudi Arabia demanding the repayment of £136m it paid out to victims of the 9/11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] A number of prominent Saudi charities and banks as well as a leading member of the al-Saud royal family were accused of being "agents and alter egos" for the Saudi state that "knowingly" provided funding to al-Qaeda and encouraged anti-Western sentiment.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Such theories have historically revolved around the putative content of the 28 pages of the 2002 report of the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Congress Joint Inquiry that were withheld from publication until July 15, 2016.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Former chief economist within the Labor Department under the Bush administration, Morgan Reynolds, argues that no planes were used in the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Reynolds claims it is physically impossible that the Boeing planes of Flights 11 and 175 could have penetrated the steel frames of the Towers, and that digital compositing was used to depict the plane crashes in both news reports and subsequent amateur video.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] "There were no planes, there were no hijackers", Reynolds insists.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] "I know, I know, I'm out of the mainstream, but that's the way it is".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] According to David Shayler, "the only explanation is that they were missiles surrounded by holograms made to look like planes", he says (although that would be well beyond the capabilities of contemporaneous hologram technology).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] "Watch footage frame by frame and you will see a cigar-shaped missile hitting the World Trade Center".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] Some truth movement veterans have repeatedly refuted the "no-plane" claims.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p01] In fact, discussion of no-plane theories has been banned from certain conspiracy theory websites and advocates have sometimes been threatened with violence by posters at other conspiracy theory websites.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] According to the 9/11 Commission Report, both black boxes from Flight 77 and both black boxes from Flight 93 were recovered.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Flight 77's CVR was said to be too damaged to yield any data.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On April 18, 2002, the FBI allowed the families of victims from Flight 93 to listen to the voice recordings.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In April 2006, a transcript of the CVR was released as part of the Zacarias Moussaoui trial.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] A series of interviews, audio and videotapes were released in the years following the 9/11 attacks that were reported to be from Osama bin Laden.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In the first of these the speaker denied responsibility for the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On September 17, 2001, in a statement issued to Al Jazeera, Bin Laden is quoted as saying: "The U.S. government has consistently blamed me for being behind every occasion its enemies attack it.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] I would like to assure the world that I did not plan the recent attacks, which seems to have been planned by people for personal reasons." Some observers, especially people in the Muslim world, doubted the authenticity of the tape.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On December 20, 2001, German TV channel Das Erste broadcast an analysis of the White House's translation of the videotape.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In an audiotape released in November 2007, Bin Laden claimed responsibility for the attacks and denied the Taliban and the Afghan government or people had any prior knowledge of the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In an interview with Al Jazeera, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed and Ramzi bin al-Shibh, two of al-Qaeda's alleged masterminds of the attacks, also confessed their involvement in the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Richard Clarke, who headed the government's anti-terrorism efforts in 2001, theorized CIA director George Tenet ordered the agency to withhold information about Nawaf al-Hazmi and Khalid al-Mihdhar from the rest of the government in an effort to cover up the agency's recruitment of the two.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] George Tenet released a statement denying the agency deliberately withheld information about the pair and noted Clarke himself said he had no proof.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In September 2000 the Project for a New American Century (PNAC) released a strategic treatise entitled *Rebuilding America's Defences*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The Defense Planning Guidance of 1992, was drafted by Paul Wolfowitz on behalf of then Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] This was described as "a blueprint for permanent American global hegemony" by Andrew Bacevich in his book *American Empire: The Realities and Consequences of U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] He said that, for this to be evidence of motive, either those responsible would have decided to openly state their objectives, or would have read the paper in 2000 and quickly laid the groundwork for the 9/11 attacks using it as inspiration.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Conspiracy theorists have questioned whether *The Oil Factor* and 9/11 provided the United States and the United Kingdom with a reason to launch a war they had wanted for some time, and suggest that this gives them a strong motive for either carrying out the attacks, or allowing them to take place.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] For instance, Andreas von Bülow, a former research minister in the German government, has argued that 9/11 was staged to justify the subsequent wars in Afghanistan and Iraq.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Former Malaysian prime minister Mahathir Mohamad was quoted as saying that there was "strong evidence" that the attacks were faked so that the United States could go to war against Muslims.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In spite of these allegations, the Bush administration specifically rejected proposals to immediately attack Iraq in response to 9/11, and acknowledged that there was no evidence of Iraqi involvement in the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Viral claims have asserted that the US government orchestrated the attacks in order to cover-up its losses of $2.3 trillion of taxpayer funds.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Rumsfeld wasn't saying the Department of Defense lost $2.3 trillion.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] He was using the number to illustrate that the department was having trouble keeping track of its finances and its spent budget because of outdated technology.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Alex Jones and other personalities hold that 9/11 was initiated by a disparate variety of banking, corporate, globalization, and military interests for the purpose of creating a globalist government.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Such New World Order conspiracy theories predate 9/11.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Conspiracy theorists often point to Operation Northwoods as a model for the 9/11 attacks, theorizing the attacks were carried out by the U.S. government as a false flag operation and then blamed on Islamic extremists.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Operation Northwoods was an unimplemented, apparently rejected, plan approved by the United States Joint Chiefs of Staff in 1962.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] One proposal in the plan suggested that covert operatives commit multiple acts of terrorism in U.S. cities and blame Cuba, thus providing a pretext for invasion.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Many individuals and organizations that support or discuss 9/11 conspiracy theories consider themselves to be part of the 9/11 Truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Prominent adherents of the movement include, among others, radio talk show host Alex Jones, theologian David Ray Griffin, physicist Steven E.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Jones, software engineer Jim Hoffman, architect Richard Gage (of Architects & Engineers for 9/11 Truth), film producer Dylan Avery, former Governor of Minnesota Jesse Ventura, former member of the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] House of Representatives Cynthia McKinney, actors Daniel Sunjata, Ed Asner, and Charlie Sheen, political science professor Joseph Diaferia and journalist Thierry Meyssan.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Adherents of the 9/11 Truth movement come from diverse social backgrounds.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The movement draws adherents from people of diverse political beliefs including liberals, conservatives, and libertarians.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The Anti-Defamation League has named Alan Sabrosky as a key figure in antisemitic 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Several of these groups have collected signatures on petitions asking for further investigation of the September 11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In 2004, John Buchanan ran for president on a "9/11 Truth" platform.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] 9/11 conspiracy theory critic Jonathan Kay asserts that for the most part proponents are not out for financial gain and in some cases have left lucrative careers to become activists.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Karen Douglas, University of Kent psychologists who specialize in conspiracy theories, examined the comments sections of over 2,000 news articles relating to the collapse of 7 World Trade Center.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] They found that proponents of 9/11 conspiracy theories were more likely to try and debunk the mainstream account than promote their own theories and also were more likely to believe in other conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Proponents of the mainstream account tended to argue for that account and showed a greater hostility toward conspiracy theory proponents.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] According to a 2011 analysis in a *Skeptical Inquirer* article, people involved in this movement, which seemingly is a disparate group with very diversified backgrounds, could be classified into three groups.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] They join the movement for different reasons, loosely self-assemble to fill different roles and are united by their shared mistrust in experts and the establishment (government and reputable sources of knowledge), and conspiratorial stance.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Through their engagement, they each find their own fulfillment and satisfaction.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Together, they contribute to the persistence, resilience and exaggerated claims of acceptance (in general public) of the movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] While discussion and coverage of these theories is mainly confined to Internet pages, books, documentary films, and conversation, a number of mainstream news outlets around the world have covered the issue.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The Norwegian version of the July 2006 *Le Monde diplomatique* sparked interest when they ran, on their own initiative, a three-page main story on the 9/11 attacks and summarized the various types of 9/11 conspiracy theories (which were not specifically endorsed by the newspaper, only recensed).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Also, on the Canadian website for *CBC News: The Fifth Estate*, a program titled, "Conspiracy Theories: uncovering the facts behind the myths of Sept.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] 11, 2001" was broadcast on October 29, 2003, stating that what they found may be more surprising than any theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On November 27, 2009, *The Fifth Estate* aired a documentary entitled *The Unofficial Story* where several prominent members of the 9/11 Truth Movement made their case.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] This article mainly attacked a group of scientists led by Professor Steven E.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Jones, now called Scholars for 9/11 Truth and Justice.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] They said "most of them aren't scientists but instructors ... at second-rate colleges".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] This view was seconded by Timothy Giannuzzi, a *Calgary Herald* op-ed columnist specializing in foreign policy.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On June 7, 2008, the *Financial Times* published a lengthy article on the 9/11 Truth Movement and 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The commentary generated over 1700 online responses, the largest in the history of the series.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In a September 2009 piece, *The Guardian* was more supportive of 9/11 conspiracy theories, asking, "when did it become uncool to ask questions?
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On September 12, 2008, Russian State Television broadcast in prime time a documentary made by Member of the European Parliament Giulietto Chiesa entitled *Zero*, sympathetic to those who question the accepted account of the attacks according to Chiesa.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] According to Thierry Meyssan in conjunction with the documentary, Russian State Television aired a debate on the subject.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The panel consisted of members from several countries including 12 Russians who hold divergent views.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The motive of Russian State Television in broadcasting the documentary was questioned by a commentator from *The Other Russia* who noted that Russian State Television had a history of broadcasting programs involving conspiracy theories involving the United States government.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On November 10, 2008, ITN broadcast a story summarizing various 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The emergence of the birther movement in 2009 has led to comparisons between that movement and the 9/11 Truth movement, with both movements seen in a very negative light.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Moon landing conspiracy theories have also been compared to the birther and 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] James Borne, a journalist for *The New York Times* who covered the September 11 attacks, described his assignment covering a 9/11 truth meeting as "[p]erhaps the most intellectually scary assignment I have had in recent years".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On August 31, 2009, the National Geographic Channel aired the program *9/11 Science and Conspiracy*, in which the Energetic Materials Research and Testing Center tested some of the claims frequently made by those who question the accepted 9/11 account.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The testing also concluded that the type of hole found at the Pentagon was consistent with the standard scenario, and that damage from a bombing or missile attack would differ from the damage that occurred.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In the program, several prominent 9/11 conspiracy theorists viewed rough edits of the experiments, and expressed their disagreement with the findings.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The British left wing magazine *New Statesman* listed David Ray Griffin as the 41st most important person who matters today.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The magazine said that Griffin's "books on the subject have lent a sheen of respectability that appeals to people at the highest levels of government".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The publication listed 9/11 conspiracy theories as "one of the most pernicious global myths".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Griffin's book *The New Pearl Harbor Revisited* was chosen by Publishers Weekly as a "Pick of the Week" in November 2008.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Denver public television KBDI-TV has aired 9/11 truth documentaries several times.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The stations spokesperson claimed airing these documentaries has been a boon for the stations fund raising efforts.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Glenn Beck, television and radio host, said of the allegations: "There are limits to debasement of this country, aren't there?
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] I mean, it's one thing to believe that our politicians are capable of being Bernie Madoff.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] It's another to think that they are willing to kill 3,000 Americans.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In March 2010, *The Washington Post* editorialized against Yukihisa Fujita, a prominent Japanese politician who has espoused 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] They described Fujita as a man "susceptible to the imaginings of the lunatic fringe".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] It went on to say that the U.S.–Japan alliance would be "severely tested" if Fujita's party continued to tolerate these kinds of comments.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] For the ninth anniversary of the attacks the Egyptian daily *Al-masry Al-youm* published an article questioning the U.S.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Government story and promoting conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The senior analyst for the semi-official Al-Ahram Center for Political and Strategic Studies and a member of Parliament from the Muslim Brotherhood was quoted.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Gordon Farrer, the technology editor for *The Age*, theorized in a November 2010 column for the *Sydney Morning Herald* that the popularity of 9/11 conspiracy theories was a result of two main factors.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] One revolved around the personality traits of the theorists themselves (cynical, anxious, belief that they are freethinkers).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The second revolved around the high internet search ranking 9/11 conspiracy theories receive, leading to a false air of authority to the theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Farrer wrote that "when politicians and media don't give them voice they feel more threatened, more suspicious, cornered, helpless; and so they go on the attack".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Geraldo Rivera, the host of *Geraldo at Large*, a news magazine run by Fox News Channel, expressed openness to questions on causes of the collapse of 7 World Trade Center.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Andrew Napolitano, a legal analyst for Fox News and former judge at the New Jersey Superior Court, voiced support for skepticism about the collapse of the high-rise building, and for Rivera investigating the event.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Alex Jones syndicated radio program was dropped by 70 radio stations when he began espousing 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On August 29, 2010, BBC Two broadcast a program entitled *The Conspiracy Files: 9/11 – Ten Years On*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On September 5, 2011, *The Guardian* published an article entitled, "9/11 conspiracy theories debunked".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The article noted that unlike the collapse of World Trade Centers 1 and 2 a controlled demolition collapses a building from the bottom and explains that the windows popped because of collapsing floors.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Toure Neblett, who has tweeted his suspicions about the attack on the Pentagon, is one of the hosts of the MSNBC program *The Cycle*, which debuted on June 25, 2012.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In 2025, The 9/11 Files was released investigating the September 11 attacks, challenging the official narrative presented in the 9/11 Commission Report.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Critics of these conspiracy theories say they are a form of conspiracism common throughout history after a traumatic event in which conspiracy theories emerge as a mythic form of explanation.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] A related criticism addresses the form of research on which the theories are based.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Eagar, an engineering professor at MIT, suggested they "use the 'reverse scientific method'.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] They determine what happened, throw out all the data that doesn't fit their conclusion, and then hail their findings as the only possible conclusion." Eagar's criticisms also exemplify a common stance that the theories are best ignored.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] "I've told people that if the argument gets too mainstream, I'll engage in the debate." According to him, this happened when Steve Jones, a physics professor at Brigham Young University, took up the issue.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Michael Shermer, writing in *Scientific American*, said: "The mistaken belief that a handful of unexplained anomalies can undermine a well-established theory lies at the heart of all conspiratorial thinking.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] All the evidence for a 9/11 conspiracy falls under the rubric of this fallacy.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Journalist Matt Taibbi, in his book *The Great Derangement*, discusses 9/11 conspiracy theories as symptomatic of what he calls the "derangement" of American society; a disconnection from reality due to widespread "disgust with our political system".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Drawing a parallel with the Charismatic Movement, he argues that both "chose to battle bugbears that were completely idiotic, fanciful, and imaginary," instead of taking control of their own lives.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] David Aaronovitch, a columnist for *The Times*, in his book entitled *Voodoo Histories: The Role of the Conspiracy Theory in Shaping Modern History* that was published in May 2009, claimed that the theories strain credulity.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] He charges that 9/11 conspiracy theorists have exaggerated the expertise of those supporting their theories, and says 9/11 conspiracy theorists, including David Ray Griffin, cross-cite each other.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] He also claims the popularity of 9/11 conspiracy theories has hurt the war on terror.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] According to Aaronovitch, because a significant portion of educated Pakistanis believe that George W.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Bush brought the towers down, dealing with the Taliban is difficult "because they actually don't believe the fundamental premise on which the war against terror was waged".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Harvard law professor Cass Sunstein co-authored a 2009 paper which used members of the 9/11 Truth movement and others as examples of people who suffer from "crippled epistemologies", to public trust and the political system.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] He wrote that "[t]hey do not merely undermine democratic debate [...] In extreme cases, they create or fuel violence.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In June 2011, the Royal Institute of British Architects (RIBA) was criticized for hosting a lecture by Richard Gage, president of Architects & Engineers for 9/11 Truth.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Rick Bell, the director of the American Institute of Architects (AIA) New York chapter, who was a witness to the 9/11 attacks, said that "no amount of money" would persuade him to allow the group to talk at his headquarters and said that Gage lacks credibility among the professional community.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Eugine Kohn, former spokesperson for the AIA, said Gage's theories were "ridiculous", "[t]here were no explosives planted", and "[t]he buildings were definitely brought down by the planes".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The decision to host the event was also criticized by the former president of RIBA and the founding president of the AIA's United Kingdom chapter.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Gage has been warned by the AIA against giving a false impression that he has a relationship with it.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] A July 2012 article in the AIA's magazine criticized Gage for continuing to intimate that he has an association with the organization, and claimed that there were no architects at an Architects and Engineers for 9/11 Truth screening held in an AIA boardroom.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] RIBA released a statement saying the perception that it endorses events held in its buildings is "regrettable", and said it would review policy on "private hire" of its buildings.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Anthony Summers and Robbyn Swan offer scathing criticism of many of the above theories in *The Eleventh Day*, their 2011 investigation of the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] King, chairmen of the House Homeland Security Committee, said 9/11 conspiracy theorists "trivialize" the "most tragic event to affect the United States" and that "[p]eople making these claims are disgraceful, and they should be ashamed of themselves".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The hosts of *The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe* (the "SGU") have spoken repeatedly about the "absurdity of 9/11 conspiracy theories".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In addition to critiquing the theories using the same or similar arguments as the above, the "SGU" hosts say that, like most conspiracy theories, this one collapses under its own weight and contradicts itself.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Former Canadian Liberal Party leader Stéphane Dion forced a candidate from Winnipeg, Lesley Hughes, to terminate her campaign after earlier writings from Hughes surfaced in which Hughes wrote that U.S., German, Russian and Israeli intelligence officials knew about the 9/11 attacks in advance.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Later, another Conservative Party candidate called for the leader of the New Democratic Party to fire a candidate for her pro-9/11 truth views.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Zijad Delic, head of the Canadian Islamic Congress, Canada's largest Muslim advocacy organization, is trying to remove 9/11 conspiracy theorists from its board, in an effort to what he describes as purifying within and totally canadianize the organization.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In 2008, calls for the resignation of Richard Falk, the special rapporteur on human rights in the Palestinian territories for the United Nations, were partially based on his support investigating the validity of 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In 2011, Falk praised a book by David Ray Griffin.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Falk was condemned for his remarks by United Nations Secretary General Ban Ki-moon and United States ambassador to the United Nations Susan Rice.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In February 2009, Aymeric Chauprade, a professor of geopolitics at CID military college in Paris, was fired by French Defence Minister Hervé Morin for writing a book entitled *Chronicle of the Clash of Civilizations* that espoused 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In September 2009, Van Jones, an adviser to US President Barack Obama, resigned after his signature on a 2004 petition calling for an investigation into whether government officials deliberately allowed the 9/11 attacks to occur and other controversial statements came to light drawing criticism.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Van Jones said he was a victim of a smear campaign, adding that he does not currently, nor ever has agreed with that theory.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The remarks prompted the United States delegation as well as others to walk out.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] President Barack Obama criticized Ahmadinejad's remarks before the United Nations General Assembly on the following day, saying that "[f]or him to make a statement like that was inexcusable" and called the remarks "offensive" and "hateful".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Previously Ahmadinejad had described the 9/11 attacks as a "suspect event" and suggested that the Bush Administration was involved in 9/11.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The Iranian president repeated his claims in 2011 with another appearance at the UN and was thereafter criticized in an article appearing in al-Qaeda's magazine, *Inspire*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The article claimed that Ahmadinejad was jealous of al-Qaeda because the stateless and under-fire Islamic terrorist organization did on 9/11 what Iran could not do.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] In 2012, Egyptian President Mohamed Morsi has called for a scientific conference to look into the events of 9/11 and speculated that the attacks were an inside job.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Although al-Qaeda occasionally brags about its "achievement," a Pew study reported in July 2011 that 75 percent of Egyptian citizens, for example, deny that Arabs carried out the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Army specialist April Gallop filed suit claiming that Vice President Dick Cheney, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld, and other Bush administration officials orchestrated the 9/11 attacks and that the Pentagon was hit by an attack ordered by Cheney.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] The suit was dismissed in 2010 by Judge Denny Chin, who said the claim was "the product of cynical delusion and fantasy".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Court of Appeals which in April 2010 issued a show cause order why the lawyers and Gallop should not be sanctioned for filing a frivolous lawsuit.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Her lawyers asked that the judges on the Court of Appeals recuse themselves because their emotions made them prejudge the case and abuse their power.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] On October 14, 2011, the judges sanctioned her lawyers $15,000 each for both the frivolous lawsuits and the accusations of prejudice.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-conspiracy-theories-p02] Gallop was not fined because of her unfamiliarity with the law.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The primary focus is on missed information that adherents allege is not adequately explained in the official National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) reports, such as the collapse of 7 World Trade Center.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] They suggest a cover-up and, at the least, complicity by insiders.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] They analyze evidence from the attacks, discuss different theories about how the attacks happened and call for a new investigation into the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Some of the organizations assert that there is evidence that individuals within the United States government may have been either responsible for or knowingly complicit in the September 11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Motives suggested by the movement include the use of the attacks as a pretext to fight wars in Iraq and Afghanistan and to create opportunities to curtail American civil liberties.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The movement lacks support from professionals in relevant fields, such as civil and aerospace engineering.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] "9/11 truth movement" is a term that has been applied to loosely affiliated organizations and individuals who allege that the United States government, agencies of the United States or individuals within such agencies were either responsible for or purposefully complicit in the September 11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The term is also being used by the adherents of the movement, who call themselves "9/11 skeptics", "truth activists", or "9/11 truthers", while generally rejecting the term "conspiracy theorists".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Adherents of the movement come from diverse social backgrounds.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The movement has drawn supporters from people of diverse political beliefs including liberals, conservatives, and libertarians.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Lev Grossman of *Time* magazine has stated that support for the movement is not a "fringe phenomenon", but "a mainstream political reality." Others, such as Ben Smith of *Politico* and the *Minneapolis Star Tribune* have stated that the movement has been "relegated to the fringe".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The movement is active in the US as well as in other countries.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In 2004, John Buchanan ran for president on a 9/11 truth platform.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jeff Boss ran in the 2008, 2012, 2016, and 2020 US presidential elections on platforms promoting the movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In a 2011 article in *Skeptical Inquirer*, Jamie Bartlett and Carl Miller gave an overview and analyzed the members of the 9/11 truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The authors found that people involved in this movement, which seemingly is a disparate group with very diversified backgrounds, could be classified into three groups.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] They join the movement for different reasons, loosely self-assemble to fill different roles, and are united by their shared mistrust in experts and the establishment (government and reputable sources of knowledge) and have a conspiratorial stance.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Together, they contribute to the exaggerated claims of acceptance (in general public) of the movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Many believers in the movement say that US government insiders played a part in the attacks, or may have known the attacks were imminent, and did nothing to alert others or stop them.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] According to these allegations, this would have given the Bush administration the justification for widespread abuses of civil liberties and to invade Afghanistan and Iraq to ensure future supplies of oil.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] A relatively common, but not exclusive view within the movement alleges that the buildings of the World Trade Center were destroyed by controlled demolition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The Internet plays a large role both in the communication between adherents and between local groups of the 9/11 truth movement and in the dissemination of the views of the movement to the public at large.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Colorado Public Television has aired several films produced by the movement such as *9/11 Explosive Evidence: Experts Speak Out*, a documentary produced by Architects and Engineers for 9/11 Truth, which once was one of the "most shared" and "most watched" programs on the national PBS site.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The station's airing of the film attracted much controversy for the affiliate and PBS.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Months before the attack, in June and July 2001, two of the conspiracy theory's earliest proponents, William Cooper and Alex Jones, claimed that the US government planned terror attacks that would be blamed on Osama bin Laden.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Both began broadcasting the "controlled demolition" conspiracy theory on the day of the 9/11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jones went on to become "one of the loudest voices in the self-styled 9/11 Truth movement".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In the aftermath of the September 11 attacks, different interpretations of the events that questioned the account given by the US government were published.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Among others, Michael Ruppert and Canadian journalist Barrie Zwicker, published criticisms or pointed out purported anomalies of the accepted account of the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] French author Jean-Charles Brisard and German authors Mathias Bröckers and Andreas von Bülow published books critical of media reporting and advancing the controlled demolition thesis of the destruction of the World Trade Center towers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In September 2002, the first "Bush Did It!" rallies and marches were held in San Francisco and Oakland, California, organized by The All People's Coalition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In October 2004, the organization 9/11 Truth released a statement, signed by nearly 200 people, including many relatives of people who perished on September 11, 2001, that calls for an investigation into the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] It also asserted that unanswered questions would suggest that people within the administration of President George W.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Bush may have deliberately allowed the attacks to happen.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In 2009, Van Jones, a former advisor to President Obama, said he had not fully reviewed the statement before he signed and that the petition did not reflect his views "now or ever".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jones, who became a leading proponent of the controlled demolition conspiracy theory, published the paper "Why Indeed Did the WTC Buildings Completely Collapse?".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] He was placed on paid leave by Brigham Young University following what they described as Jones's "increasingly speculative and accusatory" statements in September 2006, pending a review of his statements and research.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Six weeks later, Jones retired from the university.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Wide skepticism arose as to the scientific claims made by Jones and the efficacy of the peer-review process involved in the publication of his claim, and conspiracy theorists responded to criticism by positing even more elaborate and ostensible cover-ups.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In the same year, 61 legislators in the US state of Wisconsin signed a petition calling for the dismissal of a University of Wisconsin lecturer Kevin Barrett, after he joined the group Scholars for 9/11 Truth.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Citing academic freedom, the university provost declined to take action against Barrett.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Several organizations of family members of people who have died in the attacks have called for an independent investigation into the attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In 2009, a group of people, including 9/11 truth activist Lorie Van Auken and others who have lost friends or relatives in the attack, appealed to the City of New York to investigate the disaster.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The New York City Coalition for Accountability Now collected signatures to require the New York City Council to place the creation of an investigating commission on the November 2009 election ballot.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] According to some members of the 9/11 truth movement, many of the questions that the 9/11 Family Steering Committee put to the 9/11 Commission, chaired by former New Jersey Governor Thomas Kean, were not asked in either the hearings nor in the Commission Report.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Lorie Van Auken, one of the Jersey Girls, estimates that only 30% of their questions were answered in the final 9/11 Commission Report, published July 22, 2004.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In addition, *The 9/11 Commission Report: Omissions and Distortions*, written by David Ray Griffin, claimed the report had either omitted information or distorted the truth, providing 115 examples of his allegations.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Griffin has called the 9/11 Commission Report "a 571-page lie".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] McCain had written the foreword to the book *Debunking 9/11 Myths: Why Conspiracy Theories Can't Stand Up to the Facts*, published by the magazine *Popular Mechanics*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Arizona Republican State Senator Karen Johnson joined the protest in support.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] On June 10, Johnson with Gadsby as her guest and other 9/11 truth movement members in the audience, spoke before the Arizona State Senate espousing the controlled demolition theory and supporting a reopening of the 9/11 investigation.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Following the initial government investigation, the Federal Emergency Management Agency issued FEMA 403 in May 2002, titled *World Trade Center Building Performance Study: Data Collection, Preliminary Observations, and Recommendations*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) subsequently issued final reports on building collapse in 2005 and 2008.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Numerous responses to these reports were written by members of the 9/11 truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jones, then a professor at Brigham Young University, announced a paper criticizing the NIST Report and describing his hypothesis that the WTC towers had been intentionally demolished by explosives.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] This paper garnered some mainstream media attention, including an appearance by Jones on MSNBC.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] This was the first such programming on a major cable news station.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jones was criticized by his university for making his claims public before vetting them through the approved peer review process.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] He was placed on paid leave and has since retired.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Accordingly, in April 2007, some 9/11 victims' family members and some members of the new *Scholars for 9/11 Truth and Justice* submitted an additional request for correction to NIST, containing their own views on the defects in the report.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] NIST responded to this request in September 2007 supporting their original conclusions; the originators of the request wrote back to them in October 2007, asking them to reconsider their response.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Members of the movement distributed pamphlets that they say told the "truth" about the attacks at the National September 11 Memorial & Museum when the Museum opened in May 2014.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Since the publication of the official reports, a number of interconnected 9/11 truth movement organizations have been formed.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Architects & Engineers for 9/11 Truth is an organization of architectural and engineering professionals who support the World Trade Center controlled demolition conspiracy theories and are calling for a new investigation into the destruction of the Twin Towers and WTC 7.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Richard Gage, a San Francisco Bay area-based architect, founded *Architects & Engineers for 9/11 Truth* in 2006.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Investigations by the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) have concluded that the buildings collapsed as a result of the impacts of the planes and of the fires that resulted from them.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] To support its position, the group Architects & Engineers for 9/11 Truth points to the "free fall" pace of the collapse of the buildings, the "lateral ejection of steel", and to the "mid-air pulverization of concrete", the "molten metal", among other things.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The organization co-sponsored opinion polls conducted by the U.S. market research and opinion polling firm Zogby International that have shown substantial numbers of people believing the government did not tell the full truth about the September 11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The original Scholars for 9/11 Truth was founded by James H.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Fetzer, a former philosophy professor, and physicist Steven E.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] It was a group of people of differing backgrounds and expertise who rejected the mainstream media and government account of the September 11 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Initially, the group invited many ideas and hypotheses to be considered.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] However, leading members soon came to feel that the inclusion of some theories advocated by Fetzer—such as the use of directed energy weapons or miniature nuclear bombs to destroy the Twin Towers—were insufficiently supported by evidence and were exposing the group to ridicule.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] By December 2006, Jones and others set up a new scholars group, Scholars for 9/11 Truth and Justice, which described its focus as the use of scientific analysis.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The original members took a vote on which group to join and the majority voted to move to the new group.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Scholars for 9/11 Truth & Justice (STJ) formed in January 2007 and is a self-described "group of scholars and supporters endeavoring to address the unanswered questions of the September 11, 2001 attack through scientific research and public education".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The group is composed of more than 900 members, including Richard Gage, Steven E.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Jones, Jim Hoffman, David Ray Griffin, and former Congressman Daniel Hamburg.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Most members support the conspiracy theory that the World Trade Center Towers and the third skyscraper, WTC 7, were destroyed through explosive demolition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In 2008 and 2009, several members of the Scholars for 9/11 Truth & Justice published essays in science and engineering journals.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In April 2008, a letter by some of its members, was published in *The Open Civil Engineering Journal*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In October 2008, a comment by STJ member James R.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Gourley describing what he considers fundamental errors in a Bažant and Verdure paper was included in an issue of the *Journal of Engineering Mechanics*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] In April 2009, Danish chemist and STJ member Niels H.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Harrit, of the University of Copenhagen, and eight other authors, including some STJ members, published a paper in *The Open Chemical Physics Journal*, entitled *Active Thermitic Material Discovered in Dust from the 9/11 World Trade Center Catastrophe*.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The paper, which caused the editor and only peer-reviewer, Professor Pileni, to resign, claiming it was published without her knowledge, concludes that chips consisting of unreacted and partially reacted nano-thermite ("super-thermite") appear to be present in samples of the dust.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] 9/11 Citizens Watch was formed in 2002 by John Judge and Kyle Hence and, along with the Family Steering Committee, played an active role in calling for the establishment of the 9/11 Commission, and monitoring the commission closely.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Founded in 2011 by Senator Mike Gravel, the 9/11 Commission Campaign's objective is to enact subpoena-capable, state-level commissions through state ballot initiatives, namely in Oregon, Alaska and California.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] These commissions are envisioned as citizen-driven, independent organizations that would form a semi-unified grassroots national presence by exercising joint powers authority.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The Hispanic Victims Group is a group created after the 9/11 attacks, founded by William Rodriguez, a supporter of the 9/11 truth movement.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] The group was one of the key forces behind the creation of the 9/11 Commission.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] William Rodriguez, as founder of the group, was a member of the Families Advisory Council for the Lower Manhattan Development Corporation (LMDC).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Members of the 9/11 truth organizations, such as 911truth.org and Scholars for 9/11 Truth and Justice, held meetings and conferences to discuss ongoing research about 9/11 and to strategize about how best to achieve their goals during the early 2000s and 2010s.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Many of these conferences are organized by 911truth.org, and some have been covered by the international media.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Matt Taibbi of *Rolling Stone* assessed that the movement "gives supporters of Bush an excuse to dismiss critics of this administration", and expressed concerns about the number of people who believe in 9/11 conspiracy theories.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) engineering professor Thomas W.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Eagar was at first unwilling to engage with the claims of the movement, saying that "if (the argument) gets too mainstream, I'll engage in the debate".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Then, recycling some of the right's sophistry techniques, such as using long lists of supposed evidence to overcome the lack of any real evidence, the 'truthers' cherry-picked a few supposed 'anomalies' to build an 'inside-job' story line".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/11-truth-movement] Al-Qaeda has sharply criticized Iran's ex-president, Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, over his suggestions that the US government was behind the September 11 attacks, dismissing his comments as "ridiculous".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 28 September 1969 to elect the members of the 6th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) remained the largest single party in the Bundestag, winning 237 of the 518 seats.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the election, the SPD formed a coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) and the former's leader Willy Brandt became the first Social Democratic Chancellor in West Germany's history, bringing an end to 20 years of CDU/CSU rule.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the resignation of Chancellor Ludwig Erhard on 1 December 1966, a grand coalition of Christian Democrats and Social Democrats had governed West Germany under Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger (CDU), with SPD chairman Willy Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Minister of Economic Affairs Karl Schiller (SPD) had proposed revaluing (increasing the external value of) the Deutsche Mark, West Germany's currency, to reduce the country's inflation rate and the rate of growth of the country's businesses' income.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] He also sought to reduce West Germany's economic dependence on the exports.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] However, Finance Minister Franz-Josef Strauss (CSU) rejected the Deutsche Mark's revaluation because Bavarian farmers, an important part of his constituency, opposed it.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] The European Economic Community's food commodity prices were paid in U.S. dollars, and the Deutsche Mark's revaluation would have made West German exports less competitive (i.e. more expensive for other Western Europeans to buy).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] The coalition had already effectively ended before the election because of the revaluation dispute.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, enough West German voters were willing to give the Social Democratic leader, Foreign Minister Willy Brandt, a chance to govern West Germany.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt, who ran for the third time after 1961 and 1965, had shown sympathy towards groups, including left-wing intellectuals and activists of the German student movement, who had felt ignored by the Christian Democrat-led coalition governments.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, his intellect, self-control and reputation for honesty appealed to ordinary West Germans.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Willy Brandt, against the will of several party fellows like Herbert Wehner or Helmut Schmidt, chose to leave the grand coalition with the CDU/CSU, forming a social-liberal coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) instead.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] On 21 October 1969 he was elected Chancellor of Germany, the first SPD chancellor in the postwar period, after the last Social Democrat holding this position had been Hermann Müller from 1928 to 1930.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] FDP chairman Walter Scheel succeeded Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt's government proceeded with the revaluation Schiller had proposed, raising the value of the mark by 9.3% in late October.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Disappointed Kiesinger bitterly complained about the faithless liberals.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Though he had again achieved the plurality of votes for the CDU, he had to lead his party into opposition.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] He was succeeded as chairman by Rainer Barzel in 1971.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] However the Cabinet Brandt I could only rely on an absolute majority (*Kanzlermehrheit*) of twelve votes in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1969-west-german-federal-election] Several party switches in protest against Brandt's *Ostpolitik* of FDP and SPD members resulted in the snap election of 1972.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 16 October 1994 to elect the members of the 13th Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU alliance led by Helmut Kohl remained the largest faction in parliament, with Kohl remaining Chancellor in a narrowly re-elected coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] This elected Bundestag was the largest in history until 2017, numbering 672 members.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Even though this election did not lead to a switch in government, it saw the election of many people to the Bundestag who would play an important role later.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Future CDU leaders Friedrich Merz and Armin Laschet were first elected to the Bundestag in 1994, as were future cabinet ministers Norbert Röttgen and Peter Altmaier.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] This was the last election until 2009 that a centre-right government was elected.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) let its members elect a candidate for chancellor against Helmut Kohl after SPD leader Björn Engholm and chancellor candidate-designate had to resign in 1993 amid scandal.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Rudolf Scharping, Minister-President of Rhineland-Palatinate, beat Gerhard Schröder and Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul in the SPD's internal election.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Scharping was only elected with 40 percent of the vote and relied on campaigning with other SPD leaders and rivals such as Oskar Lafontaine and Gerhard Schröder, both self-confident and outspoken, in a "troika".
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Tension between them greatly hurt his campaign.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] In addition, Scharping was seen as a weak leader due to his lack of charisma and media skills, and therefore did not induce a lot of enthusiasm.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] For the first time in their existence, Alliance 90/The Greens seemed to be willing to join a government in case a centre-left SPD–Greens coalition had a workable majority in the Bundestag.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The election also saw a "red socks" campaign used by the centre-right, including the CDU/CSU and the Free Democratic Party (FDP), to scare off a possible red–red–green coalition (SPD–Party of Democratic Socialism (PDS)–Greens).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Analysts have stated that such a strategy likely paid off, as it was seen as one of the decisive elements for the narrow victory of Kohl for the CDU/CSU–FDP.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The campaign was criticized as an obvious attempt to discredit the whole political left; the PDS reinterpreted it for itself by printing red socks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP was able to continue in power with Helmut Kohl as chancellor.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] The PDS won four constituency seats in its power base of the former East Berlin, qualifying it for proportional representation even though the party won 4.4 percent of the vote, just short of the 5% electoral threshold required for full parliamentary status.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit regional parties, any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/1994-german-federal-election] This was the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that the FDP was not the third-largest party in the chamber.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] Koch-Lorber Films released the film on DVD in the US in 2007.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] Fledgling distributor Transmedia Pictures gave the film a limited release in the United Kingdom and Ireland, releasing the film on 14 September 2007.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] It was released on DVD in the UK by High Fliers Films in September 2009.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] Aztec International released the film in Australia, licensing the DVD rights to Madman Films.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] In September 2007 French language television station TV5 broadcast a reduced version of the film, running at 90 minutes—22 minutes shorter than the original French theatrical version.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] This version begins on September 6, 2001, when Irène brings Orlando and David to her apartment, removing the opening scene on Orlando's farm and the aborted hotel meeting with Elliot.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] As such it removes September 5 from the narrative.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] The version of the film was released in Portugal in November 2006 had a slightly longer running time; A number of extra scenes were included in this version at producer Paulo Branco's request.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] This version opens with Irène in her apartment receiving a letter from Elliot.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] It also includes scenes of Orlando target practicing on her farm and of Irène and William Pound sitting in his truck reminiscing on their shared history.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/a-few-days-in-september] Reviews of the film were mixed to negative, with Rotten Tomatoes giving the film a 44% rating.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Adolf Spies von Büllesheim was born in Haus Hall in Ratheim, district of Heinsberg, in North Rhine-Westphalia, property of the baronial Spies von Büllesheim family since the 18th century.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] He was the son of Egon Franz Freiherr Spies von Büllesheim and his wife Maria (born Freiin von Oer).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After school in Erkelenz he studied German law and farming at universities in Cologne and in Bonn.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After university he worked as a farmer and a lawyer from 1960 to 1997.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Since 1952 Spies von Büllesheim was a member of the CDU political party.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1969 to 1972 he was mayor of Hückelhoven.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1972 to 1987 Spies von Büllesheim was member of the German Bundestag for Heinsberg.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Spies von Büllesheim was married to Gräfin Maria Immaculata (born Concha) von Mirbach-Harff, Freiin von Vittinghoff (1938–2002), and together they had six children.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] CDU Hückelhoven.de: Die CDU Hückelhoven trauert um ihren Ehrenvorsitzenden Dr.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] Bülow, a member of the Bülow family, served as secretary of state in the German Federal Ministry of Defence (1976–1980) and Minister for Research and Technology (1980–1982), both during the Chancellor Helmut Schmidt administration, and was regarded as a "rising star" of German politics at the time.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] He served for 25 years as an SPD member of the German parliament (1969–1994).
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] In the late eighties and early nineties, he served on the parliamentary committee on intelligence services ("Parlamentarischer Kontrollausschuss").
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] This committee supervises German intelligence agencies and has access to classified information.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] His first major publication dealing with this realm, *In the Name of the State* (German: *Im Namen des Staates*) is a heavily referenced and extensive study focusing mostly on the CIA.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] Since leaving the Bundestag, he has largely left the SPD's political loop.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] Bülow wrote a book called *The CIA and 11 September* (German: *Die CIA und der 11.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] September*), in which he implies US government complicity in the September 11, 2001 attacks.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] Planning the attacks was a master deed, in technical and organizational terms.
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] To hijack four big airliners within a few minutes and fly them into targets within a single hour and doing so on complicated flight routes!
[src:andreas-von-bülow/andreas-von-bülow] That is unthinkable, without backing from the secret apparatuses of state and industry.
